<P>
 Britain OKs Non-Prescription Tagamet: SmithKline Beecham said the British 
Department of Health has approved its best-selling peptic ulcer drug for 
over-the-counter sale.It is the first time Tagamet 100 has been approved for 
non-prescription sale anywhere, a company spokesman said. Marketing the drug 
directly to consumers is expected to boost Tagamet's declining market share. 
Last year, prescription sales declined 6% from the year before. The patent for 
Tagamet expires in the United States in May, and analysts are concerned that 
SmithKline revenue could be badly hurt by generic competition. 
