<HEADLINE>
<P>
WITH OR WITHOUT PARENTS: A CHANCE FOR YOUNG PLAYWRIGHTS AT FEST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LYNNE HEFFLEY, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Are you the next Mamet? A future Marsha Norman? A budding Neil Simon? If 
you're an up-and-coming playwright, 19 years old or younger, the Blank Theatre 
Company is interested in your creative efforts. 
</P>
<P>
 The company is accepting submissions for its second annual Young Playwrights 
Festival through April 20, 1994. No pot of gold awaits, but winners will have 
their plays done by professional actors and directors in public staged readings 
in June. 
</P>
<P>
 In addition, professional playwrights, dramaturgs or script development people 
will mentor the winners and help them ready their work for performance. 
</P>
<P>
 The plays can be of any length, on any subject and must be original (and 
legible, please). Playwrights must postmark their efforts by April 20 and 
include a cover sheet with name, date of birth, school (if any), home address 
and home phone number. Send copies only; scripts will not be returned.  
</P>
<P>
 Last year's submissions explored a wide range of issues, from gays in the 
military and date rape to mid-life crisis and AIDS. The winning works were 
performed by such TV and film pros as Ed Asner, Kim Walker and Allison Smith. 
</P>
<P>
 Send scripts to the Blank Theatre Company, Young Playwrights Festival, 1301 
Lucile Ave., Los Angeles, Calif. 90026. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Don't get steamed, Barney. One of the hottest-selling kidvids going is the 
Alphabet Factory's "Firetrucks to the Rescue," a parade of historic and modern 
real-life fire trucks, equipment and action scenes set to a John Phillips Sousa 
beat. The tapes are also used by fire departments across the country to teach 
fire safety, and Alphabet Factory, a company that specializes in factual, "how 
does it work" videos, is offering to donate the tapes free of charge to fire 
departments for that purpose. Interested fire officials can call Douglas Katz 
at (800) 852-1479. Interested consumers can order the tapes for $19.95 plus 
shipping by calling (800) 862-0616. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Popular children's recording artist and Learning Channel host Rory follows up 
her last release, the show-tune-filled "Rory's Little Broadway," with a new 
movie- music tribute, "Rory's Little Hollywood." The Sony Wonder album, set for 
release March 22 on audiocassette and CD, includes tried-and-true songs from 
"The Wizard of Oz," "The Muppet Movie," "Willy Wonka & the Chocolate Factory" 
and "Hans Christian Andersen." 
</P>
