<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
March 10, 1994, Thursday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Sports; Part C; Page 9; Column 1; Sports Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
154 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
HEARING IS MARCH 19 FOR BIG 'CAP APPEAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BOB MIESZERSKI 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A hearing to consider an appeal of The Wicked North's disqualification in last 
Saturday's $1-million Santa Anita Handicap is scheduled for March 19 at Santa 
Anita. 
</P>
<P>
 After The Wicked North was moved from first to fourth by the stewards for 
alleged interference early in the stretch, owner Philip Hersh and trainer David 
Bernstein appealed. 
</P>
<P>
 Steven Schwartz was named the hearing officer by the California Horse Racing 
Board. Schwartz also served in that capacity when the connections of Tight Spot 
appealed their colt's disqualification in the 1990 Del Mar Derby. That decision 
was overturned. 
</P>
<P>
 After Schwartz hears the matter, he will recommend a decision to the CHRB at 
its next general meeting. The CHRB then makes its decision in executive 
session. 
</P>
<P>
 Stuka was given the victory after the disqualification, but the winner's share 
of the purse ($550,000) is being held in escrow. BOB MIESZERSKISANTA ANITA 
HANDICAP 
</P>
</TEXT>
