<HEADLINE>
<P>
A CRITICAL LOOK AT WOMEN OF MTV 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ZAN DUBIN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Chapman University today will screen the video that MTV doesn't want you to 
see. "Dreamworlds," one of Chapman's Women's History Month presentations this 
month, excerpts 165 MTV music videos for a scathing indictment of the way they, 
and by association, the cable-TV channel, portray women. 
</P>
<P>
 "Dreamworlds" producer Sut Jhally, who teaches at the University of 
Massachusetts at Amherst, says that his film "makes the argument that what we 
see in rock videos is the male-fantasy dream world."  
</P>
<P>
 MTV threatened -- but never followed through on -- a threat to block the 
exhibition of Jhally's 1990 video, which has since been distributed to some 
1,500 colleges and universities around the country, he said. 
</P>
<P>
 It will be shown at 11 a.m. in Chapman's Argyros Forum, room 202, 333 N. 
Glassell St., Orange. Free. (714) 997-6961. ZAN DUBIN 
</P>
</TEXT>
